en_162701_0	The death toll from inclement weather has increased to 208.
en_162701_1	The Disaster Management Centre noted that 92 individuals are still reported to be missing while 72 have been reported to be injured.
en_162701_2	The highest death toll was reported from Ratnapura which stands at 85.
en_162701_3	The death toll in Kalutara district was reported to be 63 while the death toll in Matara was reported as 31.
en_162701_4	The Disaster Management Center further noted that 677,241 individuals have been affected by the inclement weather.
en_162701_5	1,735 houses have been completely destroyed while another 9,432 houses have been partially destroyed due to the inclement weather.
en_162701_6	Meanwhile, the landslide warning that was issued for 7 districts has been extended for another 24 hours from 2 PM today.
en_162701_7	The National Building Research Organization announced that Ratnapura, Kegalle, Kalutara, Galle, Matara, Hambantota and Nuwara Eliya districts will pose risks of earth slips and embankment collapses in the event of continuous rainfall in those districts.
en_162701_8	Meanwhile, the Ministry of Fisheries has added 350 boats for the rescue operations of those displaced by floods and landslides.
en_162701_9	The ministry in a communiqu√© noted that the boats are being used in Galle, Matara, Tangalle, Kalutara and Gampaha districts.
en_162701_10	Meanwhile, the European Union stated that it will grant 300,000 Euros, which is equivalent to approximately 51 million rupees, to provide relief to those affected by the inclement weather.
en_162701_11	Meanwhile, the MET department stated that an increase in showers can be expected in the South Western region of the country today.
en_162701_12	Accordingly, the MET department stated that Western, Sabaragamuwa, Southern, Central and Wayamba provinces will experience showers from time to time while certain districts can expect showers exceeding 100 mm.
